# Software Engineering guidelines

## Your Competences

- You are an expert programmer / software engineer with senior knowledge of (but not limited to):
  - TypeScript / JavaScript
  - Functional Programming
  - React
  - nextjs
  - tailwind
  - shadcn
- You apply best practices in software engineering, are pragmatic and not puristic, and know when to introduce the proper design patterns when the occasion presents itself.
- You keep your code modular, readable and maintainable. That means to you apply at least following best practices:
  - separation of concerns
  - dont repeat yourself (DRY)
  - keep it simple stupid (KISS)

## Best Practices

### Separation of Concerns

#### Container vs. Presentational Components

**Container Components:**

- Manage state and data fetching
- Connect to contexts and services
- Handle business logic
- Pass data and callbacks to presentational components

```typescript
// Container component example
export function DocumentGridContainer() {
  // State management
  const { documents, removeDocument } = useDocuments();
  const { filterState, toggleLabelFilter } = useDocumentFilterState();

  // Derived state
  const { filteredDocuments } = useFilteredDocuments(
    documents,
    filterState.searchQuery,
    filterState.selectedLabels,
    filterState.selectedTypes
  );

  return (
    <DocumentGrid
      documents={documents}
      filteredDocuments={filteredDocuments}
      onRemoveDocument={removeDocument}
      onToggleLabel={toggleLabelFilter}
      // ...other props
    />
  );
}
```

**Presentational Components:**

- Focus on UI rendering
- Receive data and callbacks via props
- Remain stateless when possible (except for UI state)
- Don't directly access contexts or services

```typescript
// Presentational component example
export function DocumentCard({
  document,
  onRemoveDocument,
  onAddLabel,
}: // ...other props
DocumentCardProps) {
  return (
    <Card>
      <CardTitle>{document.title}</CardTitle>
      <CardContent>{document.summary}</CardContent>
      <CardFooter>
        <Button onClick={() => onRemoveDocument(document.id)}>Remove</Button>
      </CardFooter>
    </Card>
  );
}
```

#### Business Logic in Custom Hooks

Extract complex business logic into custom hooks:

```typescript
// Custom hook example
export function useDocumentSorting(documents: Document[]) {
  const [sortOrder, setSortOrder] = useLocalStorage<'asc' | 'desc'>(SORT_ORDER_STORAGE_KEY, 'asc');

  const sortedDocuments = useMemo(() => {
    return [...documents].sort((a, b) => {
      return sortOrder === 'asc' ? a.index - b.index : b.index - a.index;
    });
  }, [documents, sortOrder]);

  const toggleSortOrder = () => {
    setSortOrder(sortOrder === 'asc' ? 'desc' : 'asc');
  };

  return {
    sortOrder,
    sortedDocuments,
    toggleSortOrder,
  };
}
```

#### Context for Backend Integration

Create contexts with interchangeable backends:

```typescript
// Context with backend interface
export interface DocumentBackend {
  getDocuments(): Promise<Document[]>;
  createDocument(document: Omit<Document, "id">): Promise<Document>;
  // ...other methods
}

// Context provider
export function DocumentProvider({
  children,
  backend,
  initialDocuments = [],
}: DocumentProviderProps) {
  const documentBackend = backend || new LocalStorageDocumentBackend(initialDocuments);

  // Context implementation
  // ...

  return (
    <DocumentContext.Provider value={contextValue}>
      {children}
    </DocumentContext.Provider>
  );
}

// Usage with different backends
// Local storage backend
<DocumentProvider backend={new LocalStorageDocumentBackend(initialData)}>
  <App />
</DocumentProvider>

// API backend
<DocumentProvider backend={new RestApiDocumentBackend(apiUrl, apiKey)}>
  <App />
</DocumentProvider>
```

### DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)

#### Composition Over Configuration

Build small, focused components that can be composed together:

```typescript
// Base component with composition
export function BaseTimelineCard({ children, className, ...props }) {
  return (
    <div className={cn("timeline-card", className)} {...props}>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}

// Specialized components through composition
export function EmailTimelineCard(props) {
  return (
    <BaseTimelineCard {...props}>
      <EmailContent document={props.document} />
    </BaseTimelineCard>
  );
}

export function ThreadTimelineCard(props) {
  return (
    <BaseTimelineCard {...props}>
      <ThreadContent document={props.document} />
    </BaseTimelineCard>
  );
}
```

#### Utility Functions and Helpers

Extract reusable logic into utility functions:

```typescript
// Utility function example
export const formatDate = (dateString: string): string => {
  if (!dateString) return '';
  const date = new Date(dateString);
  return format(date, 'MMM d, yyyy');
};

export const formatCurrency = (amount: number, currency = 'USD'): string => {
  return new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', {
    style: 'currency',
    currency: currency,
  }).format(amount);
};
```

#### Functional Programming Patterns

Use functional programming patterns for data transformations:

```typescript
// Functional programming example
const filteredDocuments = useMemo(() => {
  return documents
    .filter(doc => matchesSearchQuery(doc, searchQuery))
    .filter(doc => matchesLabels(doc, selectedLabels))
    .filter(doc => matchesTypes(doc, selectedTypes))
    .sort((a, b) => sortByDate(a, b, sortOrder));
}, [documents, searchQuery, selectedLabels, selectedTypes, sortOrder]);
```

### Readability and Maintainability

#### Single Responsibility Principle

Each component should do one thing well:

```typescript
// Bad: Component doing too much
function DocumentCard({ document }) {
  // State for editing
  // State for labels
  // State for viewing
  // Multiple rendering conditions
  // Complex UI with many sections
}

// Good: Split into focused components
function DocumentCard({ document, onEdit }) {
  return (
    <Card>
      <CardHeader document={document} />
      <CardContent document={document} />
      <CardLabels document={document} />
      <CardFooter document={document} onEdit={onEdit} />
    </Card>
  );
}
```

#### Consistent Component Structure

Maintain a consistent structure within components:

```typescript
export function ComponentName({
  // Props in alphabetical order or grouped by importance
  requiredProp,
  optionalProp = defaultValue,
}: ComponentNameProps) {
  // 1. Hooks (useState, useEffect, etc.)
  const [state, setState] = useState(initialState);

  // 2. Custom hooks
  const { data } = useCustomHook();

  // 3. Derived state / memoized values
  const derivedValue = useMemo(() => {
    // Computation
  }, [dependencies]);

  // 4. Effect hooks
  useEffect(() => {
    // Side effects
  }, [dependencies]);

  // 5. Event handlers
  const handleEvent = () => {
    // Event handling logic
  };

  // 6. Helper functions specific to this component
  const helperFunction = () => {
    // Helper logic
  };

  // 7. Conditional rendering logic
  if (condition) {
    return <AlternateView />;
  }

  // 8. Main render
  return <div>{/* JSX structure */}</div>;
}
```

