#### Component Variants

Use component variants for different styles:

```typescriptreact
interface ButtonProps extends React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  variant?: "default" | "outline" | "ghost";
  size?: "sm" | "md" | "lg";
}

export function Button({
  variant = "default",
  size = "md",
  className,
  ...props
}: ButtonProps) {
  return (
    <button
      className={cn(
        "button-base",
        variant === "default" && "bg-primary text-white",
        variant === "outline" && "border border-primary text-primary",
        variant === "ghost" && "text-primary hover:bg-primary/10",
        size === "sm" && "text-sm py-1 px-2",
        size === "md" && "py-2 px-4",
        size === "lg" && "text-lg py-3 px-6",
        className
      )}
      {...props}
    />
  );
}
```

### Performance Optimization

#### Memoization

Use `useMemo` and `useCallback` to prevent unnecessary recalculations and re-renders:

```typescript
// Memoize expensive calculations
const sortedDocuments = useMemo(() => {
  return [...documents].sort((a, b) => a.index - b.index);
}, [documents]);

// Memoize callbacks to prevent unnecessary re-renders
const handleRemove = useCallback(
  (id: string) => {
    removeDocument(id);
  },
  [removeDocument]
);
```

#### React.memo for Components

Use `React.memo` for components that render often but with the same props:

```typescript
const MemoizedComponent = React.memo(function Component(props) {
  // Component implementation
});
```

### Animation and Transitions

#### Framer Motion for Animations

Use Framer Motion for animations:

```typescriptreact
import { motion } from 'framer-motion';

// Simple animation
<motion.div
  initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
  animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
  exit={{ opacity: 0 }}
  transition={{ duration: 0.3 }}
>
  Content
</motion.div>

// Animation variants
const variants = {
  hidden: { opacity: 0, y: 20 },
  visible: { opacity: 1, y: 0 },
  exit: { opacity: 0 }
};

<motion.div
  variants={variants}
  initial="hidden"
  animate="visible"
  exit="exit"
>
  Content
</motion.div>
```

#### Animate Presence for Exit Animations

Use AnimatePresence for exit animations:

```typescriptreact
import { AnimatePresence, motion } from 'framer-motion';

function List({ items }) {
  return (
    <AnimatePresence mode="popLayout">
      {items.map(item => (
        <motion.div
          key={item.id}
          initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
          animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
          exit={{ opacity: 0 }}
          layout
        >
          {item.content}
        </motion.div>
      ))}
    </AnimatePresence>
  );
}
```

### Error Handling

#### Error Boundaries

Use error boundaries to catch and handle errors:

```typescriptreact
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';

function ErrorFallback({ error, resetErrorBoundary }) {
  return (
    <div role="alert">
      <p>Something went wrong:</p>
      <pre>{error.message}</pre>
      <button onClick={resetErrorBoundary}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}

function App() {
  return (
    <ErrorBoundary
      FallbackComponent={ErrorFallback}
      onReset={() => {
        // Reset the state of your app
      }}
    >
      <YourComponent />
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}
```

#### Try-Catch in Async Functions

Use try-catch blocks in async functions:

```typescript
async function fetchData() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('/api/data');
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    const data = await response.json();
    return data;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error fetching data:', error);
    // Handle error appropriately
    throw error; // Re-throw if needed
  }
}
```

### Testing

#### Component Testing

Test components with React Testing Library:

```typescript
import { render, screen, fireEvent } from "@testing-library/react";
import { Button } from "./Button";

describe("Button", () => {
  it("renders correctly", () => {
    render(<Button>Click me</Button>);
    expect(screen.getByRole("button")).toHaveTextContent("Click me");
  });

  it("calls onClick when clicked", () => {
    const handleClick = jest.fn();
    render(<Button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</Button>);
    fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button"));
    expect(handleClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);
  });
});
```

#### Hook Testing

Test custom hooks with React Hooks Testing Library:

```typescript
import { renderHook, act } from '@testing-library/react-hooks';
import { useCounter } from './useCounter';

describe('useCounter', () => {
  it('should increment counter', () => {
    const { result } = renderHook(() => useCounter());

    act(() => {
      result.current.increment();
    });

    expect(result.current.count).toBe(1);
  });
});
```

### Conclusion

These guidelines represent our collective experience and best practices for React and Next.js development. By following these principles, we can ensure that our codebase remains maintainable, scalable, and consistent.

Remember that these guidelines are not rigid rules but rather a framework to help make decisions. Use your judgment and adapt these practices to the specific needs of your project.
